## Getting Started

1. Verify the FORGE plugin is installed — `/now` should be available in Claude Code
   (if not: `claude plugin marketplace add Renozoic-Foundry/forge-public`, then `/plugin install forge@forge`)
2. Run `/onboarding` — the one-time guided setup (required before other commands; skipped automatically if already complete)
3. Run `/now` to see the current project state
4. Run `/spec <description>` to create your first spec
5. Run `/implement <spec-number>` to start building

## How This Project Works

This project uses [FORGE](https://github.com/Renozoic-Foundry/forge-public) (Framework for Organized Reliable Gated Engineering) for spec-driven, evidence-gated development.

**Two hard rules:**
1. Every change has a matching spec
2. Every session ends with a session log

### Specs as Context Anchors

Specs are more than task descriptions — they are **context anchors** that persist decision context across AI sessions, team changes, and time. When a new session begins, the spec carries forward the *why* behind each decision, not just the *what*. This means context survives session boundaries instead of being lost and rediscovered. Rahul Garg's writing on [context anchoring](https://martinfowler.com/articles/reduce-friction-ai/context-anchoring.html) (2026, published on martinfowler.com) validated this pattern, though FORGE has practiced it from the start: every spec is a living document that prevents context loss in AI-assisted workflows.

